Raycast allows you to create custom providers, enabling you to extend its functionality with your own data and services. A custom provider lets you integrate APIs or other services directly into Raycast, allowing you to call them with a specific keyword or trigger.

To create a custom provider in Raycast, follow these steps:

1. Set Up Raycast Developer Mode

First, ensure that Raycast Developer Mode is enabled. You'll need this to create and test custom scripts and providers.

  • Open Raycast and go to the Settings.
  • Under the Extensions section, enable Developer Mode.

2. Create a New Extension

Youll need to create an extension that defines your custom provider.

  • In Raycast, open the Extensions tab and click Create New Extension.
  • Select Script Command or API Command depending on your needs. A Script Command is more flexible, while an API Command is more structured for server-based integrations.

    3. Define the Custom Provider

    Now, define the provider by creating a new script or API. If you are working with an API, you'll generally need to define:
  • API Endpoints: Define the API endpoints you want to call.
  • Authorization: If the API requires authorization, include the necessary tokens or authentication methods.
  • Data Mapping: Parse the returned data in a way that makes sense for Raycast, so you can display it properly in the interface. For example, a simple API provider might look like this in JavaScript:

const fetch = require('node-fetch');

   async function fetchData() {
     const response = await fetch('https://api.example.com/data');
     const data = await response.json();
     return data;
   }

   fetchData().then(data => {
     console.log(data);
   });

4. Integrate with Raycast UI

You'll also need to create a UI for the results. You can use Raycast's built-in UI components to display your data in a list, table, or other formats.

Here's a simple example in JavaScript (React-like syntax for Raycast components):

const { List } = require('@raycast/api');

   async function fetchData() {
     const response = await fetch('https://api.example.com/data');
     const data = await response.json();
     return data;
   }

   function renderItems(data) {
     return data.map((item, index) => (
       <List.Item key={index} title={item.title} subtitle={item.description} />
     ));
   }

   async function main() {
     const data = await fetchData();
     return <List>{renderItems(data)}</List>;
   }

   main();

5. Test and Debug

After defining your provider, you can test it within Raycast to ensure that it works as expected. Use the Raycast Console to debug and check for errors during development.

6. Publish (Optional)

Once you're happy with your provider, you can either keep it private for personal use or publish it to the Raycast Store if it's something you think others could benefit from.

If you're looking for more specific help, feel free to share details about the API or the service you're trying to integrate with Raycast!
